# Spelling & copy

All user-visible text must be spell-checked before finishing edits. This includes case study copy, project metadata, nav labels, buttons, alt text, and page titles.

## Language

- Use **British English** spelling unless matching an existing proper noun or quoted product name (e.g. `Personalised`, `behaviour` if already used nearby).
- Prefer **sentence case** for body copy.
- Case study section headings (`CaseStudyH2`, `CaseStudyH3`, `CaseStudySubheading`): follow **title case** — see `case-study-headings.mdc`.

## Brand & product names (do not “fix” these)

- **FreshPrints** — one word, capital F and P (not “Fresh Prints”).
- **Saltbot**, **Saltmine**, **Kalash**, **Piggy**, **Cisco**, **DALL-E**, **Mixpanel**.

## Services & metadata conventions

Match existing case study patterns in `src/lib/project-content.ts`:

- `Micro-interactions` (hyphenated, plural)
- `Conceptualization`
- `UX / UI for Mobile` or `UX / UI for desktop + mobile`
- `Motion Graphics`, `UX Research`, `Dev handoff`

## Before committing copy changes

1. Re-read every string you added or changed aloud.
2. Fix typos in titles, services, client/location fields, and long-form paragraphs.
3. Run `npm run spellcheck` and resolve or add legitimate terms to `cspell.json`.

## Common mistakes to catch

- Recommendation (not Recomendation)
- Research (not Reserch)
- Conceptualization (not Conceptulaization)
- dashboards, signals, ecosystem — plural/agreement and capitalization
- Duplicate vs duplicated — use the form that fits the sentence
